\f1\i\b0 \cf2 The Garden-Wave Framework in the Song of Songs \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\i0 \cf2 From Fragrance to Flame\
\
The Song of Songs, often misunderstood as mere romantic poetry, reveals a profound spiritual architecture through its imagery of fragrance, gardens, and flame. Solomon, in his most mystical work, encodes a wave-pattern of relational, theological, and cosmic truth where fragrance symbolizes spiritual initiation, the garden represents covenantal intimacy, and the flame embodies the consuming divine presence.\
\
This Garden-Wave framework moves from delicate allurement to consuming union, echoing the spiritual rhythms of faith, hope, and love while challenging modern sentimental views of both intimacy and worship.\
\
I. The Garden-Wave as Biblical Architecture\
\
The Garden-Wave framework reflects divine patterns embedded in the Hebrew Scriptures. Song of Songs does not stand alone but harmonizes with the Garden of Eden, the Temple, and the New Creation:\
	\'95	The Garden: Relational Covenant and Delight.\
	\'95	The Wave: Growing Momentum and Spiritual Transformation.\
	\'95	The Flame: Divine Consummation and Eternal Communion.\
\
Key Verse:\
\'93Awake, O north wind, and come, O south! Blow upon my garden, that its spices may flow out.\'94 (Song 4:16)\
\
