\
Hebrew Root: Gan (
\f3 \uc0\u1490 \u1463 \u1468 \u1503 
\f2 ) \'96 Enclosed Garden, Protected Space.\
	\'95	Physical Root: A walled enclosure, cultivated and secure.\
	\'95	Theological Echo: Covenant intimacy, belonging, and delight.\
\
The Garden Wave in Song of Songs:\
	\'95	4:12: \'93A garden locked is my sister, my bride, a spring enclosed.\'94\
	\'95	6:2: \'93My beloved has gone down to his garden, to the beds of spices.\'94\
	\'95	7:12: \'93Let us rise early to the vineyards, let us see if the vine has budded.\'94\
\
The Wave of the Garden:\
	\'95	Intimacy deepens as covenant begins to take root.\
	\'95	The garden\'92s enclosure signifies safety, commitment, and trust.\
	\'95	The fruits suggest the nourishment that true covenant brings.\
\
Contrast with Pagan Idolatry:\
	\'95	Pagan temples depicted gardens as sensual excess and mysticism.\
	\'95	The biblical garden reveals delight in restraint, commitment, and faithfulness.\
\
